<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 93 / Commodities and Agriculture: India sanctions more cotton
sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KUNAL BOSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CALCUTTA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE INDIAN federal government has sanctioned an additional cotton export
quota of 500,000 bales (170 kg each) for the cotton season which began in
September 1992.
Earlier, anticipating a bumper cotton crop and, consequently, a domestic
price collapse, the government released 1m bales for export.
Officials say that the only way domestic cotton prices can be maintained at
above the recommended minimum level is by stepping up exports. World prices
for cotton are higher than Indian prices by at least 10 per cent at present.
In 1991-92 India imported 300,000 bales of cotton.
</TEXT>
