<HEADLINE>
FT  09 FEB 93 / State move boosts US gun control supporters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US GUN control advocates believe they may have made an important
breakthrough with the likely passage of a law controlling handgun sales in
Virginia, one of the principal markets in the eastern US.
Mr Douglas Wilder, the state's governor, yesterday announced a compromise
bill that slightly eases his original proposal to limit buyers to one
handgun per month.
Mr Wilder, who campaigned briefly last year for the Democratic party's
presidential nomination, secured support from Republicans in the state
legislature by agreeing to allow people to buy more than one handgun a
month, provided they obrained a certificate from the state police.
The Virginia legislation is viewed as important since the state - because of
its very loose controls - has been a major source of guns used by criminals.
New York police have found than more than a quarter of weapons used in
crimes there originated in Virginia.
'This proposal will do the job to stop trafficking and proliferation of
handguns in our state,' said Mr Randolph Rollins, Virginia's secretary of
public safety.
But the 'one gun a month' approach is also attracting interest on the
national level, because its commonsense simplicity appears to have
confounded opponents of gun control.
Gun controls advocates have mostly worked on two types of restriction: a ban
on multiple shot automatic and semi-automatic weapons, and a mandatory
waiting period before a buyer can take a weapon home.
Legislation imposing such a waiting period passed Congress last year in a
comprehensive crime bill but was vetoed by President George Bush. It became
known as the Brady bill after Mr James Brady, the former White House press
secretary who was shot during an assassination attempt on President Ronald
Reagan in 1981.
Senator Howard Metzenbaum and Congressman Charles Schumer are expected to
reintroduce the Brady bill in Congress this month. President Bill Clinton
said during his election campaign that he would support the bill, as well as
a ban on semi-automatic assault weapons.
More than 90 per cent of those questioned in a recent Gallup poll favoured a
national waiting period, and support for an outright ban on handgun
possession, although still in a minority, has risen from 31 per cent to 43
per cent over the last decade.
The US criminal justice system is 'on a fast track to collapse' because of
excessive concentration on drug offences, the American Bar Association has
warned.
The ABA's criminal justice section reported that drug offences were pushing
other cases off court calendars and that long mandatory sentences ordered by
Congress were forcing states to release violent criminals to make room for
drug offenders.
The number of adult drug offenders in prison quadrupled between 1986 and
1991, six times as fast as other offences, while surveys indicated that the
proportion of the population using drugs fell from 12 per cent to 6 per
cent.
</TEXT>
